      "desc": "Handling of animals.",
      "narrative": "- On Monday April 13, 2026 there was an incident which occurred in an exhibit housing a pair of hyenas and a group of\nAfrican Painted Dogs. The two groups of animals share an interior building but are always separated. During routine\nevening closing, a zoo employee accidentally opened the wrong shift door. Employees immediately realized the error but\nbefore the door could be closed, the female hyena pushed through and gained access to the group of painted dogs. This\nresulted in a fight between the hyena and a female painted dog. Zoo personnel spent several minutes attempting to\nseparate the animals, and were eventually able to move the hyena back to her enclosure and close the shift doors to\nseparate the two groups. The encounter resulted in severe bite wounds to the hind leg of the female painted dog. She\nwas rapidly transported to the veterinary hospital and underwent immediate surgery. At the time of the inspection, the\npainted dog is alive and undergoing ongoing treatment for her injuries.\nAnimals must be handled in a manner that prevents trauma and injury. This incident allowed accidental contact between\ntwo groups of animals meant to be kept separate and resulted in serious injuries to one animal. The zoo has already\ninitiated corrective actions, including retraining of the employee in question.\nCorrect from this date (17 April 2026) forward\nThis inspection and exit interview were conducted with facility representative.\nn"
    }
  ],
  "narrative": "2.131(b)(1)  Critical\n   \nHandling of animals. \n- On Monday April 13, 2026 there was an incident which occurred in an exhibit housing a pair of hyenas and a group of \nAfrican Painted Dogs. The two groups of animals share an interior building but are always separated. During routine \nevening closing, a zoo employee accidentally opened the wrong shift door. Employees immediately realized the error but \nbefore the door could be closed, the female hyena pushed through and gained access to the group of painted dogs. This \nresulted in a fight between the hyena and a female painted dog. Zoo personnel spent several minutes attempting to \nseparate the animals, and were eventually able to move the hyena back to her enclosure and close the shift doors to \nseparate the two groups. The encounter resulted in severe bite wounds to the hind leg of the female painted dog. She \nwas rapidly transported to the veterinary hospital and underwent immediate surgery. At the time of the inspection, the \npainted dog is alive and undergoing ongoing treatment for her injuries. \nAnimals must be handled in a manner that prevents trauma and injury. This incident allowed accidental contact between \ntwo groups of animals meant to be kept separate and resulted in serious injuries to one animal. The zoo has already \ninitiated corrective actions, including retraining of the employee in question. \nCorrect from this date (17 April 2026) forward \n \nThis inspection and exit interview were conducted with facility representative. \n \n n",
